  "prompt": "How long is a business considered a \"start-up\" for?",
  "response": "The term \"start-up\" doesn't have a strict duration, but it's generally used to describe a new business in its early stages of development. Different sources and experts may define the life cycle of a start-up in varying ways, but here are some common perspectives:\n\n1. **Age of the Business**: A business is typically considered a start-up for the first 1 to 3 years after its founding. During this time, the focus is often on product development, market research, and gaining initial traction.\n\n2. **Stage of Development**: Some definitions emphasize the stage of growth rather than the age of the company. A business may still be classified as a start-up as long as it is in a phase of rapid growth, innovation, and experimentation, regardless of how many years it has been operating.\n\n3. **Funding Rounds**: Start-ups are often defined by their funding stages. For instance, if a company is seeking venture capital or undergoing seed funding rounds, it may still be considered a start-up even if it has been operating for several years.\n\n4. **Market Entry**: A business focused on developing a new product or entering a new market may be seen as a start-up until it achieves a certain level of market penetration or stability.\n\nIn summary, while \"start-up\" typically refers to businesses in their infancy (often within the first few years), it can also relate to the business's growth stage and operational context.",
